LiftFuel architecture plan

Product scope
- Mobile-first nutrition planning app named LiftFuel.
- Users create an account, complete onboarding, log meals by photo or manual entry, view calculated daily plans, track totals/streaks/check-ins, and review progress trends.

Module structure
- app/: mobile app source, navigation shell, screens, theme, assets, and platform configuration.
- app/src/navigation/: root navigator, auth stack, onboarding flow, main tab navigation, and route types.
- app/src/theme/: color tokens, typography, spacing, radius, shadows, component variants, and shared primitives.
- app/src/api/: API client, request/response types, auth/session helpers, error normalization, and storage adapters.
- app/src/features/auth/: sign-up, sign-in, session persistence, account settings entry points.
- app/src/features/onboarding/: step definitions, profile capture flow, validation, and completion state.
- app/src/features/profile/: profile model binding, editable profile screen, unit preferences.
- app/src/features/food-log/: meal log list, photo capture, storage upload, AI estimation review, manual search/edit, daily totals.
- app/src/features/plan/: calorie and macro calculation engine, training/rest day rules, plan screen UI.
- app/src/features/home/: dashboard composition, on-track status, streaks, check-ins, quick actions.
- app/src/features/progress/: weigh-ins/body metrics capture, trend charts, historical summaries.
- app/src/lib/: shared date, units, validation, formatting, storage, and test utilities.
- backend/: service entry point, routes/controllers, persistence schema, auth middleware, storage integration, AI adapter, and background-safe domain services.
- backend/src/domain/: shared business logic for profiles, food entries, plan calculation, streaks, and progress aggregates.
- backend/src/db/: migrations, schema definitions, repositories, and seed/test fixtures.
- packages/shared/ or shared/: cross-boundary TypeScript types and validation schemas used by app and backend when the chosen stack supports it.

Shared types and data model
- Account: id, email, password/auth provider metadata, createdAt, updatedAt.
- Session: access token, refresh token or secure cookie session, expiry, user id.
- Profile: user id, display name, birth date/age, sex, height, weight, goal, activity level, training schedule, dietary preferences, units.
- FoodEntry: id, user id, date, meal type, photo asset id, items, calories, protein, carbs, fat, confidence/source, notes, createdAt, updatedAt.
- FoodItem: name, quantity, serving unit, calories, protein, carbs, fat, source, optional external search id.
- DailyPlan: user id, date, calories, macros, training/rest classification, calculation inputs/version.
- DailyTotals: date, consumed macros/calories, remaining values, on-track status.
- CheckIn/Streak: date, completion state, streak count, missed days.
- ProgressEntry: date, weight, body measurements/photos if supported, notes.
- ApiError: code, message, field errors, retryable flag.

Issue dependency map
- #1 creates the app shell and navigation needed by all screens.
- #2 establishes visual primitives used by every UI issue.
- #3 creates the backend/API contract used by auth, profile, food log, plans, and progress.
- #4 depends on #3 and supports #5.
- #5 depends on #4 and unlocks authenticated app state.
- #6 depends on #1, #2, and #5.
- #7 depends on #3 and supports onboarding/profile/plan logic.
- #8 depends on #1, #2, #5, and #7.
- #9 depends on #7 and #8.
- #10 depends on #3 and authenticated users from #5.
- #11 depends on #10 and platform media permissions/storage.
- #12 depends on #10 and #11, with AI adapter isolated behind a backend service.
- #13 depends on #10 and can share edit/review UI with #12.
- #14 depends on #1, #2, #10, #11, #12, and #13.
- #15 depends on #7 and should be implemented as pure, unit-testable core logic.
- #16 depends on #7 and feeds #15/#17/#18.
- #17 depends on #15 and #16.
- #18 depends on #10, #15, and #16.
- #19 depends on #10 and #18.
- #20 depends on #17, #18, and #19.
- #21 depends on #7 and #3.
- #22 depends on #21 and can also incorporate #10/#18 history.
- #23 should cover #15, #16, totals, streaks, validation, and API client edge cases.
- #24 should audit all completed user-facing flows for loading, empty, error, offline, and permission-denied states.
- #25 depends on the full stack and validates sign-up through onboarding, meal logging, plan/home/trends, and release configuration.

Key design decisions
- Keep business rules for plan calculations, day classification, daily totals, and streaks pure and framework-independent so they can be tested early and reused by UI/backend.
- Treat the backend as the source of truth for authenticated data; the mobile app may cache server responses locally but should resolve conflicts through explicit refresh and save flows.
- Define API payloads with shared schemas where possible to avoid drift between client and server.
- Store food photos separately from food log rows; log rows reference immutable photo asset metadata and derived AI/manual estimates.
- Make AI calorie/macro estimation asynchronous at the API boundary even if the first version waits inline, so later retries or provider changes do not reshape the client.
- Separate auth/session state from profile completion state; a signed-in user can be routed to onboarding until required profile fields are complete.
- Normalize dates around user-local calendar days for logs, plans, streaks, and progress views.
- Keep UI navigation route names stable and typed from issue #1 so later screen work does not require route churn.
- Use explicit empty/error/loading states per feature rather than relying on global fallbacks.
- Add tests first around calculation-heavy modules before broad UI end-to-end coverage.
